    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1902-12-09T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1902-12-09T00:00:00-05:00" n="26"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d26">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Hay</persName> to Mr. <persName
                            type="to">Seeger</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1902-12-09">
                            <hi rend="italic">December 9, 1902</hi>.</date>
                    </dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 302.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: The Department has given consideration to Mr.
                    Bryan’s Nos. 441, 444, 464, and 466, of the respective dates of August 14,
                    August 19, October 31, and November 7, 1902.</p>
                <p>No. 441 transmits a copy of an official order of the minister of finance by which
                    he attempts to close the free navigation of the Amazon by subjecting all goods
                    in transit to Brazilian export and import duties.</p>
                <p>No. 444 reports a correction of the order so as to make it apply only to goods
                    going to and coming from Bolivia.</p>
                <p>No. 464 reports the protests of the French and German ministers against the
                    order.</p>
                <p>No. 466 reports the French Government’s approval of its minister’s protest.</p>
                <p>The Department notes by Mr. Bryan’s No. 464 that it is the common belief of the
                    diplomatic corps that the order would be rescinded by Baron Rio Branco upon his
                    assumption of the office of minister for foreign affairs. It is hoped that by
                    the time this instruction reaches you this expected action will have been taken.
                    If not, you will make proper and temperate remonstrance against the measure,
                    which, if persisted in, could not fail to injure United States commerce with the
                    Amazon region.</p>
                <p>I am, etc.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">John Hay.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
